				'starttime','00:08:05.69:00',
				'endtime','00:09:05.10:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Mr. Faulkner, I had&mdash;have down here on a list several words that I
						would like to ask you about. It's&mdash;one is the word "pussel-gutted." You spoke
						about Jewel calling his horse "pussel-gutted," and that was in mock
						affection. And then in another place Peabody&mdash;this is in, by the way, in <em>As I Lay Dying</em>&mdash;Peabody has "pussel-gutted" himself
						eating cold greens. I suppose that means make yourself flabby.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Bloated, yes.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>That's a Georgia term. I know that term.</p>
<p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Is there a plant that you're&mdash;that is behind that figure of speech,
						pussel?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>No.</p>
<p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>There's a plant in Virginia called <span class="unclear tooltip" title="Text was unclear">[pussley]</span>, and
						I thought maybe it was the same thing. It's a hideous plant, an ugly plant.
						It gets full of water.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>It could derive from that. I don't know. I've heard it all my life.
						It means someone that is bloated, that has a tremendous belly that he
						shouldn't have.</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.9">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
			try {
				QT_WriteOBJECT(
				'http://qss.itc.virginia.edu/medialab/faulkner_audio/wfaudio11_1.mp4', '300', ' 16', '',
				'autoplay', 'false',
				'scale', 'tofit',
				'starttime','00:09:05.11:00',
				'endtime','00:10:01.85:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>May I come back for a moment to this distinction between the speech
						of the Negroes and of the&mdash;of what used to be called the poor white trash. In
						your short story "Wash," Mr. Faulkner, when Wash is talking about Colonel
						Sutpen, he call&mdash;you spell it K-E-R-N-E-L, when the Negroes are talking you
						spell it C-U-N-N-E-L. Is that supposed to be "Kernal' that Wash says, and
						"Cunnel" that the Negroes say. In other words, Negroes drop the "r."</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>That's correct.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>That's the idea.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>That's correct. And the&mdash;what we call the redneck white man has a
						hard "r."</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>He has the&mdash;</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>He says "fur" for far. He says "far" for fire.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>Yes.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>The Negro don't have the hard "r."</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>I assumed that that was the purpose of that. Now if Colonel Sutpen
						or one of his&mdash;upper class characters was speaking, then you just use the
						conventional spelling, which really would be rather like Wash's
						pronunciation, though not as hard on "r"'s.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>That's right, it's between&mdash;</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>But the&mdash;between Wash and the Negroes, "Kernal" versus "Cunnel."</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Yes.</p>
<hr>
