				'starttime','00:23:00.98:00',
				'endtime','00:23:50.06:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>What about these two that are&mdash;that always have interested me:
						"dust-dark" and "dust-dawn." The time of day which is "dust-dark" and
						"dust-dawn."</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Twilight.</p>
<p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>What does "dust" mean there?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>It's "dusk" really.</p>
<p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Dusk.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>But they say "dust." That is, they say "dus-dark" and "dus-dawn."
						They don't say "dusk-dark" and "dusk-dawn."</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>If you all would let me be technical I'd say that's assimilation to
						the following "d." You see&mdash;</p>
<p><strong>Joseph Blotner: </strong>Of course.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong><span class="unclear tooltip" title="Text was unclear">[The assimilated "d."]</span></p>
<p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Dusky dark? Have you ever, Mr. Stephenson, heard "dusk-dawn," 
						"dusk-dark"?</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>No, I don't know that.</p>
<p><strong>Robert Davis: </strong>But I've heard "dust" for dusk. For the time of day, it's just
						"dust."</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.35">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
			try {
				QT_WriteOBJECT(
				'http://qss.itc.virginia.edu/medialab/faulkner_audio/wfaudio11_1.mp4', '300', ' 16', '',
