				'scale', 'tofit',
				'starttime','00:25:19.04:00',
				'endtime','00:26:21.38:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Mr. Faulkner, do you&mdash;you have&mdash;must have an astonishingly retentive
						memory for figures of speech. I noticed you spoke of a coffin "as neat as a
						sewing basket." And the talk of some women as kind of like "bees murmuring
						in a water bucket." Do you&mdash;are these phrases that are proverbial in your
						talk&mdash;in the talk of people in Mississippi, or do you make these up, or&mdash;or
						what? They're delightful phrases.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Those, I imagine, the circumstances of the story invent themselves,
						suggest to me. I've never heard them as&mdash; <span class="unclear tooltip" title="Text was unclear">[as
							analogies]</span>. Simply the circumstances of the story&mdash;or the desire
						to describe that the best I can in comprehensible phrases or figures of
						speech.</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.38">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
