				'starttime','00:26:21.45:00',
				'endtime','00:27:29.15:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Do you have any idea which kinds of things you like most to use
						figures of speech&mdash;make figures of speech out of. Flowers or fish or horses
						or dogs or trees or just&mdash;or don't you worry and care less?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>I would say that the&mdash;the&mdash;the instant I am involved
						with does the commanding in that.</p>
<p><strong>Robert Davis: </strong>I think one of the most unusual kinds of figures of speech that I've
						noticed&mdash;when certain of your characters&mdash;certain of your more perceptive
						characters like Benjy in <em>The Sound and the fury </em>and
						Darl in <em>As I Lay Dying</em>&mdash;their sense of smell seems to
						be very acute. I know Darl says&mdash;when it's getting ready to rain he says it
						smells like sulfur. Well, even Quentin in <em>The Sound and
							the Fury</em> remembers the smell of the honeysuckle and so forth. I&mdash;I
						think that's particulary good and it's rather unusual, I think. Because usually that's one
						of the senses&mdash;one of the five that's left out so often in writing. It gives
						that added touch of realism to it.</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.39">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
			try {
				QT_WriteOBJECT(
				'http://qss.itc.virginia.edu/medialab/faulkner_audio/wfaudio11_1.mp4', '300', ' 16', '',
