				'endtime','00:28:07.27:00');
		}
		catch (e) {
			//document.write(e);
		}</script><p><strong>Atcheson Hench: </strong>Mr. Faulkner, may I ask you if I&mdash;if there's something here in
						Mississippi folklore that I missed, not having grown up in Mississippi. Cora
						says, "His face looked like one of these here Christmas masts that had
						been&mdash;that had done been buried a while and then dug up." What is a Christmas
						"mast"?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Oh, the toy mask, the comic faces that children buy in the&mdash;in the
						stores for Halloween and&mdash;and Christmas time.</p>
<p><strong>Unidentified participant: </strong>And "mast" is really for "mask"?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Mask, yes.</p>
<p><strong>Unidentified participant: </strong>Just like "dusty" for "dusk."</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Yes, that's right.</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.40">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
			try {
				QT_WriteOBJECT(
				'http://qss.itc.virginia.edu/medialab/faulkner_audio/wfaudio11_1.mp4', '300', ' 16', '',
