<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>I would have to see it.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>Maybe it's a misprint?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>It is a misprint, yes. There's no such word as that. If it's not a
						misprint for "but" then&mdash;</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>"But out of the woods" would make sense. Or could it be "hot out of
						the woods"?</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>That's a good point.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>Wherever </p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>"Hot."</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>"Hot out of the woods."  I see.</p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Yes, I remember. It was hot.</p>
<p><strong>Edward Stephenson: </strong>"Hot out of the woods."  That's a misprint. </p>
<p><strong>William Faulkner: </strong>Running at top speed. Yes, "hot out of the woods."</p>
<hr>
<a name="wfaudio11_1.41">&nbsp;</a><script language="JavaScript" type="text/javascript">
